m belonging to the Habad, Gur, Mitnagdic and Sefaradi sects to those in Israel and finds many similarities between the groups. The book concludes with the proposal of an interdisciplinary model, based on the Haredi case study, which can be used by language planners worldwide to understand the issues of language maintenance and loss among ethnic and ethno-religious minorities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aAramaic languagexSocial aspectszIsrael. 0aHebrew languagexSocial aspectszIsrael. 0aHebrew language, TalmudicxSocial aspectszIsrael. 0aLanguage and languagesxReligious aspectsxJudaism. 0aUltra-Orthodox JewszIsraelxIntellectual life. 0aUltra-Orthodox JewszIsraelxLanguage. 0aYiddish languagexSocial aspectszIsrael. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / Orthodox.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311099828340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178238932340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782389323423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782389323/original  a978-3-11-099828-3  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK